"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England"},"en":{"about 1389–":"about 1389–Deceased","1440–Male":"1440–Deceased","1389–Male":"1389–Deceased","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","about 1389":"about 1389","1440":"1440","Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pepys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: (i) relationship name from the Old French personal name  <i>Pepis</i>. It is a nominative form of  <i>Pepon</i>, a French version of Continental Germanic  <i>Pipo</i>, and probably related to Old French  <i>Pepin</i>.  See  Peppin  . The personal name was extremely rare in medieval England. (ii) relationship name; alternatively it may mean; ‘Philip’s (son/relative/servant)’, from the genitive singular of Middle English * <i>Pip</i>, * <i>Pep</i>, side-forms perhaps of  <i>Phip</i>,  <i>Phep</i>, pet forms of Middle English  <i>Philip</i>,  <i>Phelip</i>.  Compare  Peppin  ,   Phippen  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Phippen","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): shortened form of the Anglo-Norman surname <i>Fitzpain</i> ‘son of <i>Pain</i>’ (see   Payne  ).","English: variant of <b>Phipp</b> with the West Midlands Middle English genitive singular <i>-en</i> instead of the more usual <i>-s</i>, see   Phipps  . Alternatively, perhaps from the unattested Middle English personal names <i>Phippon</i> or <i>Phippin</i>, which could be Old French pet forms of   Philip  , though they are not on record.","Irish: perhaps an altered form of   Thigpen   by association or confusion with the name in (1). The 17th-century <i>Thigpen</i> and <i>Phippen</i> families in NC were apparently related."]},{"name":"Peppin","meanings":["English (Somerset): variant of   Pepin  ."]},{"name":"Pipes","meanings":["English: variant of   Pipe  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":66,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Pepys was born about 1389, in Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1389–":"umbes 1389–Surnud","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1389–Male":"1389–Surnud","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","about 1389":"umbes 1389","1440":"1440","Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1389–":"noin 1389–Kuollut","1440–Male":"1440–Kuollut","1389–Male":"1389–Kuollut","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","about 1389":"noin 1389","1440":"1440","Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1389–":"environ 1389–Décédé","1440–Male":"1440–Décédé","1389–Male":"1389–Décédé","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","about 1389":"environ 1389","1440":"1440","Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Thomas Pepys est né environ 1389, à Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins